<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920204-0033</DOCNO><DOCID>920204-0033.</DOCID><HL>   Senate Counsel Subpoenas   Reporters in Hill Inquiry</HL><DATE>02/04/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>BROADCASTING (BRD)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)PUBLISHING, INFORMATION SERVICES COMPANIES (PUB)</IN><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Two reporters who broke the story aboutAnita Hill's sexual harassment allegations against ClarenceThomas have been subpoenaed by the special independentcounsel appointed by the Senate to investigate leaks to themedia.   The allegations were made before Mr. Thomas was confirmedas a Supreme Court justice.</LP><TEXT>   Peter Fleming, the special counsel, issued subpoenasordering the reporters, Timothy Phelps of Newsday and NinaTotenberg of National Public Radio, to appear before him Feb.13 and Feb. 25, respectively. The subpoenas also demand thatthey turn over documents and other materials that couldreveal information about the reporters' confidential newssources.   Lawyers for the reporters said they won't cooperate withMr. Fleming's investigation. In a letter sent yesterday tothe two ranking members of the Senate Rules Committee,Washington attorney Theodore Olson, who represents Mr.Phelps, sought to block the subpoenas, arguing that theyflout &quot;constitutional guarantees of the First Amendment.&quot;   Floyd Abrams, the attorney for Ms. Totenberg, in aninterview yesterday, called Mr. Fleming's move a &quot;futile andunconstitutional effort to force Nina to break her word toher sources.&quot;   It will be up to the Senate Rules Committee to decide whataction, if any, to take if the reporters refuse to cooperatewith Mr. Fleming.</TEXT></DOC>